

<section>
  <title>The $u$-invariant problem</title>
  <openquestion>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If $u(F) < \infty$, does there exist $B \in \N$ such that $u(F') <
        \infty$ for all $F'/F$ finite? In particular, is $B = 2u(F)$
        sufficient?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </openquestion>

  <openquestion>
    <statement>
      <p>
        When is $\tau_F$ finite?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </openquestion>

  <openproblem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find interesting classes $\mathcal F$ of fields such that for $F \in
        \mathcal F$,
        \[u(F) < \infty \Longrightarrow u(F(t)) < \infty.\]
      </p>
    </statement>
    <suggestion>
      <p>
        Examples to try:<br /><br />\[ \mathcal F  = \{F \  \ :\ \   |F^{\times}/F^{\times 2}| < \infty \}
        \]
        and
        \[  \mathcal F’ = \{F \ \ : \ \  F^{\times} = F^{\times 2} \}\]
      </p>
    </suggestion>
  </openproblem>

  <openquestion>
    <statement>
      <p>
        When $F = \R$ , we have $u(F) = \infty$ but $\tau_F < \infty$. Is there
        an example where this holds for $F$ not formally real?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </openquestion>

  <openquestion>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Define \[u_k(F) = \max \{ \dim (q)\ \ |\ \ q \in I^k \}.\]
        Then $u_0 = u$.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Can we compute $u_k(F)$? How about $u_3(F)$?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <status>
      <p>
        Note that forms in
        $I^3$ have trivial Clifford invariant.
      </p>
    </status>
  </openquestion>

  <openquestion>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find reasonable classes $\mathcal F$ of fields such that $u(F)$ is a
        power of 2 for all $F \in \mathcal F$. For these fields, assume $k$ is the
        period-index bound for $l=2$. Does this imply $u(F) = 2^{k+1}$?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <opinion>
      <p>
        I think I’ve seen this somewhere before
      </p>
    </opinion>
  </openquestion>

  <openquestion>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let \[\nu(F) = \max \{n\ |\ I^n \neq 0 \}. \]
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <statement>
      <p>
        If $\nu(F) < \infty$, is it true that $\nu(F') < \nu(F) +1$ for all
        $F'/F$ finite?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <commentary>
      <p>
        $2^{\nu(F)} < u(F)$
      </p>
    </commentary>
    <context>
      <originator>
      <person aimplid="org.aimpl.user:c"/>
      </originator>

      <p>
        This is related to the computation of Galois groups of
        quadratically closed fields.
      </p>
    </context>
  </openquestion>

  <openquestion>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        For a quadratic form $q$ over $F$, we define
        \[\textrm{splitting degree} = \min\{[L:F]\ :\ q_{L}\ \textrm{is a
        direct sum of hyperbolics}\}.\]
        The <term>torsion index</term> of $F$, denoted $\tau_F$ is the maximum
        splitting degree, taken over all even dimensional $q$.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Is $\tau_F < 2^{(\frac{u(F)}{2} -1)}$?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </openquestion>
</section>

